            "html": "<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8' standalone='yes'?><html>\n<head>\n    <meta content=\"text/html; charset=UTF-8\" http-equiv=\"Content-Type\"/>\n\n<style type=\"text/css\">/**//**/</style>\n<meta content=\"ALEXANDER Goff\" name=\"author\"/>\n<meta content=\"2018-12-08\" name=\"publicationdate\"/>\n\n<title>no title</title></head>\n<body class=\"b1\">\n\n<div id=\"content\">\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some of this information also ends up recorded in structured data, names, times, dates, addresses etc.\n\n** Basic information **\n\nThis CRIS relates to an incident of Common Assault which apparently occurred outside COMPUTERWORLD, 100 BLACKFRIARS, LONDON around 14:00 on Saturday 8th December 2018.\n\nOfficers attending\n\nAS123 SI SMITH\n5122AS SPS BROWN\n\nCAD 1234/8Dec18 refers\n\nTOA 14:55\n\nFirst aid - not required.\nSuspect not on scene.\n\n** Victim **\n\nThe victim Fred BLOGGS is a 23 year old male visiting LONDON from his home in NORWICH.  He is staying with friends in SOUTHWARK until Monday 10th December.\n\nBLOGGS said that he was walking along BLACKFRIARS road heading to meet a friend at the NOVOTEL hotel.  As he passed the entrance to COMPUTERWORLD he heard a male shout from behind.  He said that thinks he heard the words “Screw you, red shoes.  Death to anyone who wears red shoes”.  He turned to look behind him and saw a male (SUS1) running towards him and swinging his arms and fists.\n\nHe described SUS1 as being male, white (IC1), about 6’1” tall wearing blue jeans, black Adidas or Nike trainers and a yellow t-shirt with the letters “KTDD” or “KDDT” on it.\n\nBLOGGS said that he does not recognise SUS1 and has never seen him before.\n\nBLOGGS said that SUS1 continued to run towards him at some speed and did not stop when he reached him, running into him, knocking him over and then spitting on him whilst saying “Red shoes, red shoes, I hate you, red shoes”.\n\nCOMPUTERLAND allowed officers to use their offices to take an MG11 from the victim, this is scanned in the S: drive in the folder appropriate to this CRIS.\n\nThere were no visible injuries on BLOGGS who said “I’m fine, but my red shoes are important to me, I’ve had enough of the red shoes movement, they are constantly victimising me”.\n\nBLOGGS said that he was fine to return to his friends home alone and did not need first aid.\n\n** Suspect **\n\nSee above for suspect description.\n\nAfter the incident, SUS1 ran on towards SOUTHWARK UNDERGROUND STATION and the victim believes that he saw him go into the underground station.\n\n\n** Forensics **\n\nVictim had the presence of mind to retain the tissue that he used to wipe the suspects saliva.  This has been seized and exhibited as FXB/01.  It is in evidence bag MPS12345564324323 and stored in the CHARING CROSS forensic freezer under 66=43524 and 105=323.\n\nNo other forensic opportunities were available.\n\n** CCTV **\n\nCCTV enquiries undertaken at COMPUTERWORLD.  They do have a camera that covers the outside of the building but the security guard did not know how to get footage.  On Monday Graham GRHAMSON is available on 020 3424 2323 and will be able to provide.\n\nOfficers viewed CCTV in situ at SOUTHWARK UNDERGROUND STATION at 15:30.  A male matching the description given, including the distinctive t-shirt is seen to enter the station at 14:30 and use an Oyster or other payment card at Gate 4 before heading to Platform 2 and boarding a train towards SOUTHWARK.  CCTV recording seized and exhibited as NAL/01 in bvag MPS 12341241324 in CX as 66=42342 and 105=23.\n\nOfficer CW501 believes he recognises SUS1 from having previously dealt with him for burglary under CRIS 132134/16.  SUS1 may be Sam SAMUELSON, 27 The Street, ANYTOWN.  PNC ID 77323/11 CRO ID 11/324237\n\n\n** Next actions **\n\nThe victim would like us to investigate this further with a view to prosecuting.\n\nIt is my view that lines of investigation exist, specifically potential for DNA from the saliva, CCTV and a named suspect.\n\nNote that current OIC is leaving the MPS tomorrow to train to be an astronaut.  This needs to be assigned to a new OIC.\n\n</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"> </p>\n</div>\n\n</body></html>",
